    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Sri Lanka's mango season is a vibrant celebration of flavour and colour. The island grows dozens of indigenous and introduced mango varieties, from the small, intensely sweet 'Willard' to the large, fibrous 'Karutha Kolomban'. When mangoes ripen, they fill markets, roadside stalls and home kitchens with their unmistakable fragrance.</p><h2>Why Mango is Special</h2><ul><li>Dozens of unique Sri Lankan varieties</li><li>Deeply rooted in Sri Lankan culture and cuisine</li><li>Used in curries, sambols, desserts and drinks</li><li>Rich in vitamins A and C</li><li>A seasonal highlight everyone looks forward to</li></ul><h2>Popular Varieties</h2><ul><li>🟡 Willard — small, golden, intensely sweet</li><li>🟢 Karutha Kolomban — large, green-skinned, aromatic</li><li>🟠 Vellai Kolomban — pale flesh, mild sweetness</li><li>🔴 Seeni — small, deep orange, very sweet</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🥭 Eat ripe mango slices fresh</li><li>🍛 Cook into mango curry (amba maluwa)</li><li>🍹 Make mango juice, lassi or smoothies</li><li>🥒 Pick green mango as achcharu (pickle)</li><li>🍨 Blend into mango ice cream or sorbet</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> March – June, with the best harvest in April and May.</p><p>Mango orchards in Matale, Kurunegala and the dry zone come alive during this period, and fruit lovers travel to buy directly from growers.</p></section>",
