    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Jackfruit holds a special place in Sri Lankan culture and cuisine. This massive tropical fruit, which can weigh up to 30 kg, grows abundantly across the island. When unripe, it is used as a savoury vegetable; when ripe, its golden bulbs become a sweet, fragrant treat. Every part of the jackfruit is used — even the seeds are boiled and eaten.</p><h2>Why Jackfruit is Special</h2><ul><li>Sri Lanka's national fruit in cultural significance</li><li>Incredibly versatile — used sweet or savoury</li><li>Every part of the tree and fruit is utilised</li><li>Rich in fibre, potassium and vitamins</li><li>A centuries-old staple of the island's cuisine</li></ul><h2>How It's Used</h2><ul><li>🍛 Unripe jackfruit curry (kos mallung, kos atha)</li><li>🍌 Ripe jackfruit eaten fresh as a sweet snack</li><li>🫕 Jackfruit seed curry (kos badapu)</li><li>🍲 Kos porridge and traditional village dishes</li><li>🥡 Dried jackfruit chips as a popular snack</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> March – June and a secondary harvest in September – October.</p><p>During peak season, jackfruit trees laden with heavy fruits are a common sight in village gardens, and roadside vendors sell freshly cut portions across the country.</p></section>",
