    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>The wood apple is one of Sri Lanka's most distinctive seasonal fruits, known for its rock-hard brown shell and aromatic, tangy pulp inside. Despite its strong smell, the flavour is uniquely delicious — a blend of sweet, sour and fermented notes. It is used extensively in Sri Lankan cuisine and traditional medicine.</p><h2>Why Wood Apple is Special</h2><ul><li>Unique flavour unlike any other tropical fruit</li><li>Deeply embedded in Sri Lankan food culture</li><li>Used in drinks, curries, chutneys and sweets</li><li>Rich in iron, calcium and fibre</li><li>A key ingredient in traditional Ayurvedic remedies</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🥤 Wood apple juice (divul kiri) — a beloved drink</li><li>🫙 Wood apple chutney (divul achara)</li><li>🍛 Wood apple curry in traditional village cooking</li><li>🍨 Wood apple ice cream and desserts</li><li>🍯 Mixed with jaggery for a simple sweet treat</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> August – November, with the best fruit in September and October.</p><p>Wood apple trees are common in the dry zone and intermediate zone, and the fruit is a nostalgic reminder of village life for many Sri Lankans.</p></section>",
