    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Jambul, also known as Java plum or black berry, is a small, deep-purple fruit with a unique astringent-sweet flavour. It is famous for temporarily turning the tongue and lips a vivid blue-purple after eating. The fruit is widely foraged from wild trees and sold in small bunches at roadside stalls during the monsoon season.</p><h2>Why Jambul is Special</h2><ul><li>The tongue-staining effect makes it a childhood favourite</li><li>Rich in antioxidants and vitamin C</li><li>Used in traditional Ayurvedic medicine for diabetes</li><li>Grows wild — a truly natural, organic fruit</li><li>Nostalgic flavour for generations of Sri Lankans</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🍒 Eat fresh — be prepared for a blue tongue!</li><li>🫙 Preserve as jambul jam or chutney</li><li>🍹 Make into tangy fruit juice</li><li>🩺 Traditional remedy for blood sugar control</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> May – August, coinciding with the southwest monsoon rains.</p><p>Wild jambul trees are found across the island, especially in village home gardens and along railway lines. The fruit is a fleeting seasonal pleasure.</p></section>",
