    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Sri Lanka's indigenous pomegranate, known as 'deluma', is a smaller, more intensely flavoured variety than the large commercial cultivars found elsewhere. Its ruby-red seeds burst with a balanced tart-sweet juice, and the fruit has been cultivated on the island for centuries. It holds cultural significance in Buddhist and Hindu traditions.</p><h2>Why Pomegranate is Special</h2><ul><li>Indigenous variety with deeper, more complex flavour</li><li>Sacred fruit in Buddhist and Hindu traditions</li><li>Rich in antioxidants, vitamin C and potassium</li><li>Used in Ayurvedic medicine for blood purification</li><li>A beautiful, celebratory fruit for special occasions</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🍒 Extract and eat the fresh seed arils</li><li>🥗 Add to salads for colour and crunch</li><li>🍹 Press into fresh pomegranate juice</li><li>🫙 Make pomegranate molasses or chutney</li><li>🍛 Use seeds as a garnish for curries and rice dishes</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> November – February, with the best fruit during the cool dry months.</p><p>The finest pomegranates come from the dry zone regions of Hambantota, Monaragala and Anuradhapura, where the hot, dry climate produces the sweetest fruit.</p></section>",
