    category: "seasonal-foods",
    description: "The 'tree of life' fruit of the Jaffna peninsula — dark, fibrous, and deeply nourishing.",
    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>The palmyra fruit is deeply intertwined with the culture and identity of northern Sri Lanka, particularly the Jaffna peninsula. The dark, round fruit grows in clusters atop the majestic palmyra palm and contains three sweet, gelatinous kernels inside. Every part of the palmyra tree is used — from its fruit and sap to its leaves and timber.</p><h2>Why Palmyra Fruit is Special</h2><ul><li>Culturally sacred to Tamil heritage in northern Sri Lanka</li><li>The 'tree of life' — every part is used</li><li>Rich in fibre, potassium and natural sugars</li><li>Used in traditional Tamil medicine and cuisine</li><li>A symbol of resilience and self-sufficiency</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🥥 Eat the tender gelatinous kernels (palmyra sprouts)</li><li>🍬 Make into traditional jaggery (tal hakuru)</li><li>🍹 Prepare palmyra toddy (tal raa) — a traditional drink</li><li>🍮 Cook into tal palli (sweet palmyra dessert)</li><li>🍪 Palmyra flour used in traditional biscuits and sweets</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> March – July, with the best harvest in April and May.</p><p>In the Jaffna peninsula, palmyra palms dominate the landscape, and the fruit harvest is a community celebration. The fruit is also used in traditional Hindu temple offerings.</p></section>",
