    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>The bael fruit, known locally as 'modara', is a sacred fruit often found near Hindu temples and Buddhist shrines across Sri Lanka. Its hard, green-to-yellow shell encloses an aromatic, orange pulp that is both tangy and sweet. The fruit is the primary ingredient in the famous 'modara drink', a cooling summer beverage beloved across the island.</p><h2>Why Bael Fruit is Special</h2><ul><li>Sacred fruit found at temples island-wide</li><li>Cooling properties — perfect for Sri Lanka's hot season</li><li>Key ingredient in the iconic modara drink</li><li>Rich in vitamin C, potassium and fibre</li><li>Used in Ayurvedic medicine for digestive health</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🥤 Modara drink — the classic cooling summer beverage</li><li>🍧 Bael fruit ice cream and sorbets</li><li>🫙 Bael fruit jam and preserves</li><li>🍵 Bael leaf tea as a digestive tonic</li><li>🍬 Candied bael fruit as a sweet snack</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> April – August, with the best fruit in May and June.</p><p>Bael trees grow near temples and in home gardens. During peak season, vendors sell freshly prepared modara drinks on virtually every street corner.</p></section>",
