    description: "Starchy, versatile fruit that transforms into crispy chips, creamy curries and satisfying roasted snacks.",
    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Breadfruit, known as 'sinnappu' in Sinhala, is a starchy, versatile tropical fruit that has been a part of Sri Lankan cuisine since the colonial era. When cooked, its texture and flavour are remarkably similar to freshly baked bread — hence its English name. The fruit is deeply embedded in village cooking traditions, particularly in the coastal lowlands.</p><h2>Why Breadfruit is Special</h2><ul><li>Incredibly versatile — can be cooked savoury or sweet</li><li>Staple of traditional village cuisine</li><li>High in fibre, carbohydrates and essential nutrients</li><li>Sustainable and filling — feeds families economically</li><li>Colonial heritage adds to its culinary story</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🍟 Breadfruit chips — crispy, addictive street snack</li><li>🍛 Breadfruit curry (sinnappu maluwa)</li><li>🍞 Roasted breadfruit — smoky, filling treat</li><li>🥔 Mashed breadfruit as a potato alternative</li><li>🥘 Breadfruit jackfruit seed curry — a traditional combo</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> March – June and September – November.</p><p>Breadfruit trees are common in village gardens in the wet zone and coastal areas. The large, round fruits are a welcome seasonal addition to the table.</p></section>",
