    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Wael, or velvet tamarind, is a small, round wild fruit with a thin, brittle brown shell and dark, sticky pulp inside. Its tangy-sweet flavour is intensely addictive, and for generations of Sri Lankans, it evokes powerful childhood memories of foraging in village fields and forests. The fruit is still sold in small bags at roadside stalls during its brief season.</p><h2>Why Wael is Special</h2><ul><li>Deeply nostalgic — a beloved childhood fruit</li><li>Wild-harvested, completely natural</li><li>Intense tangy-sweet flavour unlike anything else</li><li>Rich in tartaric acid, vitamin C and iron</li><li>Part of Sri Lanka's traditional foraging heritage</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🍒 Peel and eat the dry pulp straight from the shell</li><li>🫙 Preserve as wael candy or sweetmeat</li><li>🍹 Make tangy wael juice or concentrate</li><li>🍬 Dry and coat with sugar for a simple treat</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> October – January, with the best fruit in November and December.</p><p>Wild wael trees grow in the dry zone scrublands and village commons. The fruit is a humble, seasonal treasure that connects urban Sri Lankans to their rural roots.</p></section>",
