    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Boiled corn on the cob is one of Sri Lanka's most iconic roadside snacks, especially popular in the cool hill-country regions. Vendors boil fresh ears of corn over charcoal stoves and serve them steaming hot, brushed with butter and sprinkled with salt and chili powder. The combination of sweet corn, rich butter, and the crisp mountain air is an unforgettable experience.</p><h2>Why Boiled Corn is Special</h2><ul><li>Iconic Sri Lankan roadside experience</li><li>Fresh, simple, and deeply satisfying</li><li>Best enjoyed in the cool hill-country climate</li><li>Rich in fibre, vitamins and natural sugars</li><li>Affordable and widely available snack</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🌽 Classic: brushed with butter and salt</li><li>🌶️ Spicy: sprinkled with chili powder</li><li>🍋 Tangy: squeezed with fresh lime</li><li>🧈 Rich: generous butter and a pinch of pepper</li><li>🏔️ Best enjoyed at a misty hill-country viewpoint</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> June – September, during the cooler months when hill-country tourism peaks.</p><p>Corn stalls line the roads between Nuwara Eliya, Ella and Hatton, serving steaming ears to passing travellers.</p></section>",
