    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Roasted sweet potato, known locally as 'bathala', is a beloved traditional evening snack in Sri Lanka. Street vendors roast whole sweet potatoes over glowing charcoal, filling the air with a sweet, caramelised aroma. The warm, soft interior and slightly charred exterior make it a deeply comforting treat, especially during the rainy season evenings.</p><h2>Why Roasted Sweet Potato is Special</h2><ul><li>Quintessential Sri Lankan street food</li><li>Deeply comforting — especially on rainy evenings</li><li>Naturally sweet, requiring no added sugar</li><li>Rich in fibre, beta-carotene and vitamins</li><li>Affordable, wholesome and satisfying</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🍠 Eat hot and fresh from the vendor's cart</li><li>🧂 Sprinkle with a pinch of salt</li><li>🍯 Drizzle with kithul treacle for extra sweetness</li><li>🍛 Boil and mash as a simple home dish</li><li>🥤 Blend into sweet potato smoothies</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Available:</strong> Year-round, but especially popular during the rainy season evenings (May – June and October – November).</p><p>Sweet potato vendors are a common sight on Sri Lankan streets, with their distinctive charcoal stoves and aromatic roasted tubers.</p></section>",
