    detail: "<section class='destination-content'><h2>Overview</h2><p>Kavum is one of the most iconic traditional sweets in Sri Lanka, deeply associated with the Sinhala and Tamil New Year celebrations. This deep-fried oil cake is made from a batter of rice flour and kithul treacle, cooked in a special clay pan called an 'attiya'. The result is a golden-brown, crispy-on-the-outside, soft-on-the-inside treat that is indispensable during festive occasions.</p><h2>Why Kavum is Special</h2><ul><li>Centrepiece of Sri Lankan New Year celebrations</li><li>A tradition passed down through generations</li><li>Made with natural ingredients — rice flour and palm treacle</li><li>The aroma of kavum frying signals the New Year</li><li>A symbol of prosperity and togetherness</li></ul><h2>How to Enjoy</h2><ul><li>🍯 Eat fresh and warm — straight from the attiya</li><li>🎁 Share with neighbours during New Year</li><li>📦 Pack as a festive gift for friends and family</li><li>☕ Enjoy with a cup of Ceylon tea</li></ul><h2>Season</h2><p><strong>Peak Season:</strong> April (Sinhala and Tamil New Year), with availability during other festivals and celebrations throughout the year.</p><p>During the New Year season, the sizzling sound of kavum being fried in clay pots fills every Sri Lankan household, marking the joyous occasion.</p></section>",
